This would return true iff the type _T_ is comparable using simple `memcmp` semantics. For instance, the primitive integral types would qualify, as would enums. Types with custom equality operators or which have overridden the `Equals` method would not qualify.

The scenario is that it would simply code like that at https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/1456a38ed9ee3eda8022b9f162a45334723a0d7a/src/System.Private.CoreLib/shared/System/MemoryExtensions.cs#L191-L206. Currently this code special-cases only `byte` and `char`, but it misses `sbyte`, `ushort`, `short`, enums, and custom structs which are simple wrappers around these types. It would be nice to be able to write something like this:

```cs
if (RuntimeHelpers.IsDefaultComparable<T>()) {
  if (Unsafe.SizeOf<T>() == sizeof(byte)) {
    // pretend that T is byte, even if it's a different type
    return ...;
  } else if (Unsafe.SizeOf<T>() == sizeof(char)) {
    // pretend that T is char, even if it's a different type
    return ...;
  }
}

// If reached this point, do element-by-element comparison
return ...;
```

This will especially come in handy if we introduce a `Utf8Char` type in the future, as extension methods on `ReadOnlySpan<Utf8Char>` would be able to go down the fast paths without the underlying code having special-cased `T = Utf8Char`.

I used  System.Data.SqlClient APIs in UWP(target version is 17134, min version is 16299).

Please see the following code sample:

`string connectionString =
        @"Data Source=172.xx.xx.xx;Initial Catalog=mydatabase;;User ID=sa;Password=Password";
            const string GetProductsQuery = "select * from table";
            try
